Subject: Anisha, 3 Steps to create a powerful personal brand on LinkedIn
Message_body:
Hi Anisha, hope you are doing well. LinkedIn is not just another social network. ItÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a place where you can create your brand and take a lot of advantages like getting your dream job or getting investments for your startup. But how to create a powerful personal brand?
The Strategy Story brings a special guide to help you out.
Ã‚Â 
3 STEP GUIDE TO CREATE A POWERFUL PERSONAL BRAND ON LINKEDIN
Ã‚Â 
1st Step
Optimize your LinkedIn Profile

Focus on writing attractive LinkedIn Summary
Have a professional profile picture (headshot)
In the About section mention your skills and area of expertise
Complete your skills and recommendation section



2nd Step
Connect with Relevant People

Connect with people strategically.
In the search filter, select the industry, function, and location where you are looking for a job
Send them a connection request with a customized message. DonÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t send a request without a message



3rd Step
Create your visibility on LinkedIn

Post meaningful content on the function you want to work in the future to show your thought leadership
Comment on other peopleÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s post-showÃ‚Â your interest in learning about new things
Start making connections from now onwards only. Build your network. Attend webinars. Be part of a community

Top 40 Relevant Idea Submissions also get INR 2000Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â 

ABOUT HACKATHON

The Telecommunications and Digital Government Regulatory Authority (TDRA) of the United Arab Emirates in cooperation with the World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS) Forum 2022 is organizing an International Hackathon across three challenge areas to promote the achievement of Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) using ICTs. The Hackathon is organized as part of TDRAÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s efforts towards the community and its responsibility to push forward digital transformation on a national level and share knowledge on international platforms. Interested stakeholders are invited to analyze available data and come up with solutions to challenges in one of the following categories.

Digital Safety: for solutions that support online safety including privacy, deterring intruders, protecting children, and detecting criminal tendencies.
	Blockchain for a better life: for blockchain solutions that improve our lives in any field such as health, transportation, service provision, and many more.
	Climate Change: for solutions that mitigate the impact of climate change or other weather phenomena on people.

Timeline and Selection Process

THEMES

Digital Safety

Blockchain for a better life

Climate Change

PRIZES

Grand Winner

1st place in each challenge category (3)

2nd place in each challenge category (3)

3rd place in each challenge category (3)

Subject: Amazon WoW Interview Update
Message_body:
Dear Candidate,

Hope you are doing well and safe today!
Thank you for taking the time to interview with Amazon. We know that the application process takes preparation and commitment, and we truly appreciate your willingness to make time to share your skills and accomplishments with us.
Unfortunately, we will not be moving forward with your candidacy at this time.
If there are other positions that interest you on Amazon.jobs, you will be eligible to reapply and re-interview after a six-month period.

We appreciate your interest in Amazon and wish you the best in your current endeavors.

Thanks & Regards,
Amazon WoW | SDE Team | Student Programs -APAC

Subject: Yale Public Health - MasterTrack Deadline Extension
Message_body:
Hello Anisha Gupta!


Join thousands of learners enrolling in Yale courses this month!


Deadline extension - Health Informatics MasterTrack


Take the next step in your biomedical, clinical, or public health career by 
exploring innovative approaches to data and knowledge management. In as 
little as seven months, earn a powerful university-issued career 
credential. Throughout four courses, you will leverage the expertise of 
faculty from the Division of Health Informatics at the Yale School of 
Public Health, learning from real-world projects and live sessions with 
groups of high-caliber peers. In the event a learner successfully completes 
the MasterTrack Program and is admitted and matriculates into the Yale 
School of Public Health MPH
 
, or Online Executive MPH
 
, the University will grant the MasterTrack student two course credits 
towards the degree program. Ready to take the next step? Enroll today - the 
next session
 
starts on November 1, 2021 and the enrollment has been extended through 
November 10.


Newly Launched Course - Introduction to Medical Software


The Introduction to Medical Software course
 
is aimed at current software engineers and students in the field. The 
course covers the use of software engineering and design in the development 
of medical devices, and includes sections on industry regulations and how 
to start a new medical venture. The course discusses applications for AI 
and machine learning in medical settings, and how to identify user needs in 
the software development cycle. Learn from Yale professors and ten industry 
experts throughout the course as they connect the course topics to real 
world applications in this growing field. 


Happy Learning!


Yale Digital Education Team


Yale University

Subject: Warming temperatures. Rising water levels. And hope.
Message_body:
Leaders from around the world are gathering this week in Glasgow, Scotland, 
United Kingdom for the United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP26). 
This summit brings much of the world together to accelerate action to 
address climate change and move toward a more sustainable future.


Our planet needs lifelong learners who can reflect on the mistakes of the 
past and find collective solutions to address these truly global 
challenges.


No matter if you only have a few hours to spare or if youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re looking to 
devote your career to address climate change Ã¢â‚¬â€ there is something you can 
explore, learn, and do with the University of Michigan on Coursera and 
Michigan Online to increase your understanding of our changing climate and 
build a more hopeful future.


Every journey to recovery begins with one step. LetÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s do it together, learn 
for good, and Learn for Our Planet
 
.


To help you get started, weÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve shared a few ways you can begin your 
learning journey and join the global conversation this week during the 
COP26 summit.


Climate Change Collection



WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ve compiled a special collection of short videos, articles, and more to 
help you better understand the dynamics of climate change, its social 
impact, and ways in which we can all enact change.


Act on Climate: Steps to Individual, Community, and Political Action



Co-developed by University of Michigan students, this course helps you to 
take action to address and respond to climate change as an individual and 
in partnership with your community and political leaders.


Beyond the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs): Addressing Sustainability 
and Development



Through the lens of the United NationsÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ 17 sustainable development goals, 
youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll explore the twin challenges of sustainability and development with 
actionable knowledge for innovating solutions. This course doubles as the 
first class in the Sustainability and Development MasterTrackÃ¢â€žÂ¢ Certificate.


Sustainability and Development MasterTrackÃ¢â€žÂ¢ Certificate
 
Ã¢â‚¬â€ Six Courses


Take a deeper dive into the UNÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s sustainable development goals to design 
solutions to address core sustainability and development challenges in the 
full MasterTrack certificate program. This certificate could help you to 
accelerate your path toward earning a graduate degree from the University 
of Michigan. See the MasterTrack description page
 
for more information.


Impacts of the Environment on Global Public Health
 
Ã¢â‚¬â€ Four Courses


See how the world around us Ã¢â‚¬â€ from what we throw away to the air we breathe 
Ã¢â‚¬â€ impacts our health every day in this course series.


Sustainable Food Teach-Out



Explore the complexities of the food system and how we can, individually 
and collectively, create food habits that reduce our impact on climate 
change.


Other Teach-Out archives:


      * Melting Ice Rising Seas Teach-Out
        


      * Earth Day at 50 Teach-Out
        


------------------------------------------


The Michigan Online Visionary Educator (MOVE) Event Series brings together 
presenters who share insights, tools, and discussions on relevant issues in 
free, synchronous online events. Please join us to engage directly with 
MOOC faculty in these two upcoming sessions.


Extended Reality for Everybody



11 a.m. ET on Thursday, November 4, 2021


Dr. Michael Nebeling from the Extended Reality for Everybody Specialization
 
and Jeremy Nelson, Director of U-MÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Extended Reality Initiative, will 
discuss the opportunities, challenges, and future of virtual reality, 
extended reality, and mixed reality Ã¢â‚¬â€ collectively known as extended 
reality (XR).


Register Here >>



Social and Emotional Intelligence



11 a.m. ET on Friday, December 3, 2021


Professors Cheri Alexander and Jeffery Sanchez-Burks will provide 
compelling and relatable insights that reveal how much of our social life 
is shaped by emotional intelligence. They will provide tips for giving 
useful feedback as well as preparing yourself to receive feedback from 
others. TheyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll also share different actionable methods for coaching, 
mentoring, and teaching in these key areas.


Register Here >>



------------------------------------------


We invite you to join us in these important conversations in our continuing 
University of Michigan Teach-Out SeriesÃ¢â€žÂ¢.


Afghan Refugees and Displaced People Teach-Out



Now - November 13


WeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll discuss the short- and long-term implications of the multi-nation 
evacuation of Afghan nationals to other countries as well as ways to raise 
awareness about whatÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s happening in Afghanistan and help displaced people 
or refugees in their own communities.


Practicing Gratitude Teach-Out



Now - November 30


Learn about the science and benefits of gratitude practices, including 
practical ways to bring it into your own life while recognizing that 
gratitude and struggle can coexist.

What is Data Structures and Algorithms?

The word Ã¢â‚¬Å“algorithmÃ¢â‚¬Â right away would make you think of technical stuff and make it seem daunting. So today, we are going to try to understand it the easy way. Spoiler alert: It is not as daunting as it sounds.

Technically speaking, an algorithm is defined as a set of rules or a step-by-step procedure that are to be executed in a specific order to get the desired output.






Characteristics of an Algorithm

The characteristics of algorithm are as follows:




UnambiguousÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 An algorithm should be clear and simple in nature and lead to a meaningful outcome i.e. they should be unambiguous.




InputÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 It should have some input values. In our scenario of baking a cake, our ingredients were the inputs




OutputÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

Ã‚Â So every algorithm should have well-defined outputs




FinitenessÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 The steps of an algorithm should be countable and it should terminate after the specified number of steps.




EffectivenessÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 Each step of the algorithm should be effective and efficient enough to produce results.




Language IndependentÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 algorithm should work for all programming languages and give the same output


To know more about characteristics of algorithm click on the button below:

Ã‚Â 







Read More






Ã‚Â 

Factors of an Algorithm

While designing an algorithm, we must consider the following factors-




ModularityÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 If a big problem can be easily broken down into smaller ones, it facilitates modularity




CorrectnessÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 The analysis of the problem statement and consequently the algorithm should be correct.




MaintainabilityÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 The algorithm should be designed in such a way that it should be easy to maintain and if we wish to refine it at some point, we should be able to do so without making major changes




FunctionalityÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 The steps of an algorithm should successfully solve a real world problem




User-friendlyÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 It should be easily understood by programmers




SimplicityÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 It should be the simplest possible solution to a problem. By simplicity, we refer to the fact that the algorithm should have the best-case time complexity.




ExtensibleÃ¢â‚¬â€œ

 It should be extensible i.e. the algorithm should facilitate reusability. In other words, other programmes should be able to reuse it or extend for their own problem statement too

Subject: Python Interview Questions to brush up on!
Message_body:
For Freshers and Experienced


Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â Ã¢â‚¬Å’Ã‚Â 
















Introduction:


						Python was developed by Guido van Rossum and was released first on February 20, 1991. It is one of the most widely-used and loved programming languages and is interpreted in nature thereby providing flexibility of incorporating dynamic semantics. It is also a free and open-source language with very simple and clean syntax.



1. What is Python?


						Python is a high-level, interpreted, general-purpose programming language. Being a general-purpose language, it can be used to build almost any type of application with the right tools/libraries. Additionally, python supports objects, modules, threads, exception-handling, and automatic memory management which help in modeling real-world problems and building applications to solve these problems.



2. What are the benefits of using Python? 




Python is a general-purpose programming language that has a simple, easy-to-learn syntax that emphasizes readability and therefore reduces the cost of program maintenance. Moreover, the language is capable of scripting, is completely open-source, and supports third-party packages encouraging modularity and code reuse.



Its high-level data structures, combined with dynamic typing and dynamic binding, attract a huge community of developers for Rapid Application Development and deployment.




3. What is an Interpreted language?


						An Interpreted language executes its statements line by line. Languages such as Python, Javascript, R, PHP, and Ruby are prime examples of Interpreted languages. Programs written in an interpreted language runs directly from the source code, with no intermediary compilation step.

ToÃ‚Â read the remaing 86 questions on Python Interview Questions click on the button below:

Ã‚Â 







Read On






Ã‚Â 



4. How is memory managed in Python? 




Memory management in Python is handled by the Python Memory Manager. The memory allocated by the manager is in form of a private heap space dedicated to Python. All Python objects are stored in this heap and being private, it is inaccessible to the programmer. Though, python does provide some core API functions to work upon the private heap space.



Additionally, Python has an in-built garbage collection to recycle the unused memory for the private heap space.







5. What is lambda in Python? Why is it used?


						Lambda is an anonymous function in Python, that can accept any number of arguments, but can only have a single expression. It is generally used in situations requiring an anonymous function for a short time period. Lambda functions can be used in either of the two ways:



Assigning lambda functions to a variable:

							mul = lambda a, b : a * b

							print(mul(2, 5)) # output => 10



Wrapping lambda functions inside another function:

							def myWrapper(n):

							return lambda a : a * n

							mulFive = myWrapper(5)

							print(mulFive(2)) # output => 10




6. How do you copy an object in Python?


						In Python, the assignment statement (= operator) does not copy objects. Instead, it creates a binding between the existing object and the target variable name. To create copies of an object in Python, we need to use the copy module. Moreover, there are two ways of creating copies for the given object using the copy module -



Shallow Copy

 is a bit-wise copy of an object. The copied object created has an exact copy of the values in the original object. If either of the values is a reference to other objects, just the reference addresses for the same are copied.



Deep Copy

 copies all values recursively from source to target object, i.e. it even duplicates the objects referenced by the source object.


						from copy import copy, deepcopy

						list_1 = [1, 2, [3, 5], 4]

						## shallow copy

						list_2 = copy(list_1)

						list_2[3] = 7

						list_2[2].append(6)

						list_2 # output => [1, 2, [3, 5, 6], 7]

						list_1 # output => [1, 2, [3, 5, 6], 4]

						## deep copy

						list_3 = deepcopy(list_1)

						list_3[3] = 8

						list_3[2].append(7)

						list_3 # output => [1, 2, [3, 5, 6, 7], 8]

						list_1 # output => [1, 2, [3, 5, 6], 4]
